customer satisfaction, delivery, and after-sales service.\"", "\"DIFFICULTIES OF SETTING TARGETS FOR QUALITATIVE AREAS\":\"Challenges in setting targets for qualitative areas include identifying drivers of improved performance, measuring qualitative factors, staff behavior in response to targets, and setting the appropriate level of difficulty for targets.\"", "\"EXAMPLE OF CALL CENTRE\":\"A call centre introduced a target of two minutes per call to increase the number of calls handled, but staff hung up on customers after two minutes to avoid a variance.\"", "\"BALANCED SCORECARD\":The Balanced Scorecard is a strategic management technique developed by Kaplan and Norton that provides top management with an integrated set of performance measures from four perspectives: financial, customer, internal business processes, and learning and growth. This approach to performance management ensures that internal systems and processes support customer and financial objectives, encourages integration between departments, and allows for performance measurement and control actions. It is used to align business activities with the vision and strategy of the organization, improve internal and external communications, and monitor organizational performance against strategic goals. The Balanced Scorecard comprises an integrated framework of financial and non-financial performance measures that aim to clarify, communicate, and manage strategy implementation across the four perspectives.", "\"BALANCED SCORECARD PHILOSOPHY\":\"The balanced scorecard philosophy involves setting measures and performance targets across four perspectives: customer, internal business process, learning and growth, and financial, ensuring that these perspectives complement each other.\"", "\"SETTING MEASURES AND PERFORMANCE TARGETS\":\"For each perspective in the balanced scorecard, management needs to identify objectives, measures, targets, and initiatives to improve performance.\"", "\"LEADING AND LAGGING INDICATORS\":\"Leading indicators predict future performance, while lagging indicators reflect past performance. Both are used in the balanced scorecard to provide a comprehensive view of performance.\"", "\"CRITICAL SUCCESS FACTOR\":\"A performance outcome that an organisation requires to achieve success.\"", "\"VALUE FOR MONEY (VFM)\":\"VALUE FOR MONEY (VFM)\" is a measure used to evaluate the performance of an organization, particularly in the public sector, based on the principles of economy, efficiency, and effectiveness. It assesses how well resources are utilized to achieve intended results. As a public sector objective, VFM involves achieving the 3Es: economy, efficiency, and effectiveness.", "\"3ES\":\"The 3Es stand for economy, efficiency, and effectiveness, which are used to achieve Value for Money (VFM) in the public sector.\"", "\"PERFORMANCE ANALYSIS IN PRIVATE SECTOR, PUBLIC SECTOR AND NOT-FOR-PROFIT ORGANISATIONS\":\"Performance analysis involves explaining and interpreting the balanced scorecard, considering external factors, and addressing specific issues in not-for-profit and public sector organisations.\"", "\"PROBLEMS OF NON-QUANTIFIABLE OBJECTIVES IN PERFORMANCE MANAGEMENT\":\"Challenges in performance management when objectives cannot be quantified, often seen in not-for-profit organisations and the public sector.\""], "parameters": {"model": "text-embedding-3-small", "temperature": 0.0, "frequency_penalty": null, "presence_penalty": null, "top_p": 1.0, "max_tokens": 4000, "n": 1}}